VALUES
(42, 23, 56, 2, 31, 14, 14, 'rested the sabbath day according to the commandment', 'Sabbath Observance Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of resting on the Sabbath as commanded in both passages. Luke 23:56 mentions resting on the Sabbath, while Exodus 31:14 emphasizes the holiness of the Sabbath and the prohibition of work.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 56, 23, 58, 13, 14, 'rested the sabbath day according to the commandment', 'Sabbath Observance Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of observing the Sabbath as a day of rest and holiness. Both passages emphasize honoring the Sabbath and refraining from personal pleasures, reflecting a commitment to God''s commandments.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 56, 24, 17, 24, 25, 'rested the sabbath day according to the commandment', 'Sabbath Observance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of resting on the sabbath day according to God''s commandment. Luke highlights the observance of the sabbath, while Jeremiah underscores the significance of hallowing the sabbath for the city''s prosperity.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 43, 20, 1, 2, 'first day of the week', 'Resurrection Morning Events', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of Mary Magdalene on the first day of the week. They describe her early visit to the sepulchre, highlighting the significance of the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 40, 28, 1, 8, 'first day of the week', 'Resurrection Announcement', 'Both passages emphasize the arrival of women at the sepulchre on the first day of the week. They highlight the significance of this visit, culminating in the announcement of Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 41, 16, 1, 8, 'first day of the week', 'Resurrection Morning Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the events occurring on the first day of the week, specifically the visit to the sepulchre by the women. They detail the women''s intentions to anoint Jesus and their discovery of the stone being rolled away, highlighting the resurrection.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 42, 24, 10, 10, 'certain others with them', 'Women at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the role of women in the resurrection narrative. The first passage introduces the women bringing spices, while the second identifies them as key witnesses to the events.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 42, 23, 55, 56, 'bringing the spices which they had prepared', 'Women at the Sepulchre', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of the women regarding the sepulchre. In Luke 23:55-56, they prepare spices and ointments, while in Luke 24:1, they bring these spices to the sepulchre early in the morning.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 40, 27, 55, 56, NULL, 'Women at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of women who followed Jesus. In Luke, women come to the sepulchre, while Matthew identifies some of these women, highlighting their role in the resurrection narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 1, 41, 15, 40, 40, NULL, 'Women at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of women at significant moments surrounding Jesus'' burial and resurrection. Luke 24:1 mentions women bringing spices, while Mark 15:40 identifies women observing from a distance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 2, 40, 27, 60, 66, 'the stone rolled away from the sepulchre', 'Resurrection and the Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the stone associated with the sepulchre. In Luke, the stone is found rolled away, indicating the resurrection, while in Matthew, the stone is sealed to prevent tampering, highlighting the concern over the resurrection claim.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 2, 40, 28, 2, 2, 'the stone rolled away from the sepulchre', 'Stone Rolled Away Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the stone being rolled away from the sepulchre, indicating the event of the resurrection. The SOURCE verse notes the discovery of the stone''s removal, while the TARGET passage describes the action of the angel rolling it back.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 2, 41, 15, 46, 47, 'the stone rolled away from the sepulchre', 'Resurrection and Burial Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the sepulchre and the stone. Luke 24:2 mentions the stone rolled away, while Mark 15:46-47 describes the stone being rolled to the door of the sepulchre, linking the burial and resurrection events.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 2, 41, 16, 3, 4, 'the stone rolled away from the sepulchre', 'Connection of the Rolled Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the stone being rolled away from the sepulchre, highlighting the miraculous event of the resurrection. The women in both accounts express concern about the stone, only to find it already moved.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 2, 43, 20, 1, 2, 'the stone rolled away from the sepulchre', 'Connection of the Stone''s Removal', 'Both passages emphasize the stone rolled away from the sepulchre, indicating the discovery of the empty tomb. This shared detail highlights the moment of revelation regarding Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 3, 42, 24, 23, 23, 'found not the body of the Lord Jesus', 'Discovery of the Empty Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the absence of Jesus'' body, highlighting the significance of the empty tomb. The first passage notes the discovery of the missing body, while the second elaborates on the implications of that discovery, including the vision of angels.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 3, 43, 20, 6, 7, 'found not the body of the Lord Jesus', 'Discovery of the Empty Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the absence of Jesus'' body in the tomb. Luke 24:3 states they found not the body, while John 20:6-7 describes the linen clothes left behind, indicating the same event of resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 3, 40, 16, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Forgetfulness and Absence', 'This connection highlights the theme of absence in both passages. In Luke 24:3, the absence of Jesus'' body signifies a pivotal moment, while in Matthew 16:5, the disciples'' forgetfulness about bread reflects a lack of awareness of their needs.', 'theme', 0.286, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 4, 41, 16, 5, 5, 'two men stood by them in shining garments', 'Angelic Appearances at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of men in shining garments at the tomb, indicating a divine encounter. The descriptions of the figures as ''two men'' in Luke and ''a young man'' in Mark suggest a shared theme of angelic beings revealing the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 4, 43, 20, 11, 12, 'two men stood by them in shining garments', 'Angels at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of two angels at the tomb of Jesus. In Luke, the angels are described as standing in shining garments, while in John, they are seated at the head and feet of where Jesus lay.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 4, 44, 1, 10, 10, 'two men stood by them', 'Angelic Presence in Key Events', 'Both passages emphasize the appearance of two men in shining or white garments during significant moments of revelation. This connection highlights the role of divine messengers at pivotal points in the narrative.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 4, 40, 28, 2, 6, 'two men stood by them in shining garments', 'Angelic Presence at Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the appearance of angels at the resurrection. In Luke, two men in shining garments are present, while Matthew describes an angel whose countenance is like lightning. This connection highlights the divine announcement of Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 4, 1, 18, 2, 2, 'two men stood by them in shining garments', 'Angelic Appearances', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of men in shining garments or divine form, highlighting moments of revelation. The perplexity in Luke mirrors the awe in Genesis when encountering these figures.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 41, 16, 5, 6, 'Why seek ye the living among the dead?', 'Resurrection Announcement Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of seeking Jesus after his resurrection. The question in Luke highlights the contrast between seeking the living and the dead, while Mark confirms Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 40, 28, 3, 5, 'Why seek ye the living among the dead?', 'Fear and Seeking the Living', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear experienced by those encountering the angelic presence. They also highlight the inquiry about seeking Jesus, who is alive, contrasting with the dead. This connection underscores the significance of recognizing Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 66, 1, 18, 18, 'the living among the dead', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of life after death. Luke 24:5 questions why one seeks the living among the dead, while Revelation 1:18 affirms that Jesus, who was dead, is now alive forevermore.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 66, 2, 8, 8, 'the living among the dead', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between death and life. Luke 24:5 questions why one seeks the living among the dead, while Revelation 2:8 affirms that the one who was dead is now alive.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 27, 10, 16, 16, 'afraid, and bowed down their faces', 'Connection of Fear and Strength', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and the loss of strength in the presence of the divine. In Luke, the fear of the women leads them to bow down, while in Daniel, the encounter with a heavenly being causes a similar loss of strength.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 42, 1, 12, 13, NULL, 'Fear and Divine Assurance', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages. In Luke 24:5, the fear of the women is met with reassurance, while in Luke 1:12-13, Zacharias experiences fear but is comforted by the angel''s message.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 5, 27, 8, 17, 18, NULL, 'Fear and Divine Encounter', 'Both passages emphasize fear and falling down before a divine presence. In Luke, the fear leads to a question about seeking the living, while in Daniel, fear results in a physical response and a call for understanding.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
